ğŸ§¾ Chemical Datasheet â€“ Potassium Chloride
Chemical Name: Potassium Chloride
Formula / Structural Diagram: KCl (Ionic compound: Kâº + Clâ»)
CAS #: 7447-40-7
Molecular Weight: 74.55 g/mol
Density: 1.984 g/cmÂ³ (at 20 Â°C)
Appearance: White crystalline solid, odorless
âš ï¸ Hazard Information
â— GHS Pictograms: âŒ (Not classified as hazardous under GHS)
â— NFPA 704 Diamond:
â—‹ Health: 1
â—‹ Flammability: 0
â—‹ Reactivity: 0
â— Hazard Statements (H-codes): Not classified as hazardous.
â— Precautionary Statements (P-codes):
â—‹ Avoid excessive exposure.
â—‹ Handle in accordance with good laboratory practices.
ğŸ§ª Properties
â— Melting Point: 770 Â°C
â— Boiling Point: 1420 Â°C (sublimes at high temp)
â— Solubility: 34.2 g/100 mL in water (20 Â°C), insoluble in alcohols
â— Vapor Pressure: Negligible
9
â— Other Notes: Commonly used in fertilizers, food (as salt substitute), and medical IV
fluids (electrolyte replenisher).
âš ï¸ Handling & Storage
â— Storage Class: General chemical storage (non-hazardous inorganic salts)
â— Conditions: Keep container tightly sealed, store in cool dry place
â— Container Type: Glass, plastic, or polyethylene containers
â— Compatible With: Most inorganic compounds
â— Incompatible With: Strong acids (may release HCl gas), strong oxidizing agents
ğŸš¨ Safety Notes
â— First Aid:
â—‹ Skin: Wash with soap and water.
â—‹ Eye: Rinse with water for several minutes, remove contacts if present.
â—‹ Inhalation: Move to fresh air if dust is inhaled. Seek medical attention if
symptoms occur.
â—‹ Ingestion: Rinse mouth with water, seek medical advice if large amounts
ingested.
â— Firefighting: Not flammable. Use extinguishing media appropriate for surroundings.
â— Spill/Leak Cleanup: Sweep up solid, avoid dust generation, place in appropriate waste
container.
10
ğŸ§‘â€ğŸ”¬ Lab Use Notes
â— PPE: Lab coat, gloves, safety goggles, dust mask if airborne particles present.
â— Handling: Avoid dust inhalation, handle with care to prevent spills.
â— Decomposition Products: At very high temperatures may release toxic potassium
oxides and chlorine gas.
â— Disposal: Dispose of in accordance with local environmental regulations; typically as
non-hazardous waste.
