ğŸ”¥â­•,
â— NFPA 704 Diamond:
â—‹ Health: 1
â—‹ Flammability: 0
â—‹ Reactivity: 0
â—‹ Special: OX (oxidizer)
â— Hazard Statements (H-codes):
â—‹ H272: May intensify fire; oxidizer.
â—‹ H319: Causes serious eye irritation.
â— Precautionary Statements (P-codes):
â—‹ P210: Keep away from heat, sparks, open flames, hot surfaces.
â—‹ P220: Keep/Store away from combustible materials.
â—‹ P280: Wear protective gloves/eye protection/face protection.
â—‹ P305+P351+P338: If in eyes: Rinse cautiously with water for several minutes.
12
ğŸ§ª Properties
â— Melting Point: 334 Â°C
â— Boiling Point: Decomposes above 400 Â°C (releases oxygen, nitrogen oxides,
potassium nitrite)
â— Solubility: 31.6 g/100 mL in water (20 Â°C), insoluble in ethanol
â— Vapor Pressure: Negligible
â— Other Notes: Strong oxidizer, widely used in fertilizers, food preservation, fireworks, and
explosives.
âš ï¸ Handling & Storage
â— Storage Class: Oxidizers (Class 5.1)
â— Conditions: Store in a cool, dry, well-ventilated area away from heat and combustible
materials.
â— Container Type: Plastic or glass containers resistant to oxidizers.
â— Compatible With: Stable with most inorganic salts and metals.
â— Incompatible With: Organic materials, sulfur, reducing agents, finely powdered metals,
strong acids.
ğŸš¨ Safety Notes
â— First Aid:
â—‹ Skin: Wash with soap and water.
â—‹ Eye: Rinse with water for several minutes, seek medical attention if irritation
persists.
â—‹ Inhalation: Move to fresh air, seek medical advice if symptoms occur.
13
â—‹ Ingestion: Rinse mouth with water, seek immediate medical advice.
â— Firefighting: Not combustible but supports combustion; use water in large amounts. Do
not use dry chemicals or COâ‚‚ extinguishers directly.
â— Spill/Leak Cleanup: Sweep up carefully, avoid dust, place in non-combustible container,
wash spill site with water.
ğŸ§‘â€ğŸ”¬ Lab Use Notes
â— PPE: Lab coat, nitrile gloves, chemical splash goggles, dust mask/respirator if dusty.
â— Handling: Avoid mixing with combustible or reducing agents. Handle with care to
prevent contamination.
â— Decomposition Products: Nitrogen oxides (NO, NOâ‚‚), potassium nitrite (KNOâ‚‚), and
oxygen gas.
â— Disposal: Dispose of in accordance with local regulations. Usually treated as hazardous
oxidizer waste.
