Appearance: White crystalline solid, odorless
âš ï¸ Hazard Information
â— GHS Pictograms: ğŸ”¥â­• (Oxidizer), âš ï¸ (Exclamation mark)
â— NFPA 704 Diamond:
â—‹ Health: 2
â—‹ Flammability: 0
â—‹ Reactivity: 1
â—‹ Special: OX (oxidizer)
â— Hazard Statements (H-codes):
â—‹ H272: May intensify fire; oxidizer.
â—‹ H319: Causes serious eye irritation.
â—‹ H335: May cause respiratory irritation.
â— Precautionary Statements (P-codes):
â—‹ P220: Keep/Store away from combustible materials.
â—‹ P280: Wear protective gloves/eye protection.
â—‹ P370+P378: In case of fire: Use water for extinction.
â—‹ P305+P351+P338: IF IN EYES: Rinse cautiously with water for several minutes.
15
ğŸ§ª Properties
â— Melting Point: 610 Â°C (decomposes before boiling)
â— Boiling Point: Decomposes on heating (releases oxygen, chlorine oxides)
â— Solubility: 1.5 g/100 mL water (25 Â°C) â€” sparingly soluble; insoluble in ethanol
â— Vapor Pressure: Negligible
â— Other Notes: Strong oxidizer, less sensitive than potassium chlorate but still hazardous
in mixtures. Commonly used in pyrotechnics, explosives, matches, and propellants.
âš ï¸ Handling & Storage
â— Storage Class: Oxidizers (Class 5.1)
â— Conditions: Store in tightly closed containers in cool, dry, well-ventilated places. Keep
away from organic or combustible materials.
â— Container Type: Non-combustible, chemical-resistant containers (glass, polyethylene).
â— Compatible With: Stable with many inorganic salts.
â— Incompatible With: Sulfur, phosphorus, metals (especially powdered), strong acids,
reducing agents, organics.
ğŸš¨ Safety Notes
â— First Aid:
â—‹ Skin: Wash thoroughly with water and soap.
â—‹ Eye: Rinse with water for several minutes, seek medical advice if irritation
persists.
16
â—‹ Inhalation: Move to fresh air, provide oxygen if breathing is difficult, seek
medical help.
â—‹ Ingestion: Rinse mouth with water, seek immediate medical advice.
â— Firefighting: Not combustible itself but releases oxygen; use large amounts of water. Do
not use COâ‚‚, dry chemicals, or foam.
â— Spill/Leak Cleanup: Avoid dust generation, sweep carefully, collect in clean
non-combustible containers, wash areas with plenty of water.
ğŸ§‘â€ğŸ”¬ Lab Use Notes
â— PPE: Lab coat, nitrile gloves, chemical goggles, dust mask/respirator in case of airborne
particles.
â— Handling: Avoid friction, shock, and contamination with combustibles. Handle only with
clean tools and surfaces.
â— Decomposition Products: Oxygen gas, chlorine oxides, potassium chloride.
â— Disposal: Dispose of as hazardous oxidizing waste according to local regulations. Do
not mix with organic waste streams.
