â— Disposal: Treat as hazardous oxidizer; follow local regulations for disposal. Do not
release into the environment.
âš ï¸ Note: Strontium nitrate is a strong oxidizer used in pyrotechnics to produce red flames. It
can react explosively with organic materials or reducing agents. Extreme care is required during
handling, storage, and disposal.
74
ğŸ§¾ Chemical Datasheet â€“ Strontium Peroxide
Chemical Name: Strontium Peroxide
Formula / Structural Diagram: SrOâ‚‚
CAS #: 1313-86-2
Molecular Weight: 109.62 g/mol
Density: 4.12 g/cmÂ³
Appearance: Yellowish-white crystalline solid
âš ï¸ Hazard Information
â— GHS Pictograms: ğŸ”¥ (Oxidizer), âš ï¸ (Exclamation mark), â˜ ï¸ (Toxic)
â— NFPA 704 Diamond:
â—‹ Health: 3
â—‹ Flammability: 0
â—‹ Reactivity: 3 (oxidizer, explosive potential with combustible materials)
â—‹ Special: OX (oxidizer)
â— Hazard Statements (H-codes):
â—‹ H272: May intensify fire; oxidizer.
â—‹ H302: Harmful if swallowed.
â—‹ H319: Causes serious eye irritation.
â—‹ H335: May cause respiratory irritation.
â—‹ H410: Very toxic to aquatic life with long-lasting effects.
â— Precautionary Statements (P-codes):
â—‹ P220: Keep/Store away from combustible materials.
â—‹ P261: Avoid breathing dust.
75
â—‹ P280: Wear protective gloves/eye protection.
â—‹ P301+P310: IF SWALLOWED: Immediately call a POISON CENTER/doctor.
â—‹ P501: Dispose of contents/container in accordance with local regulations.
ğŸ§ª Properties
â— Melting Point: Decomposes above ~500 Â°C
â— Boiling Point: Decomposes; does not boil under normal conditions
â— Solubility: Slightly soluble in water; reacts with acids to release oxygen
â— Vapor Pressure: Negligible at room temperature
â— Other Notes: Strong oxidizer used in pyrotechnics and oxygen generation. Reacts
violently with organic materials, reducing agents, and acids.
âš ï¸ Handling & Storage
â— Storage Class: Oxidizers (Class 5.1)
â— Conditions: Store in a cool, dry, well-ventilated area away from heat, organic materials,
fuels, and acids. Keep the container tightly closed.
â— Container Type: Glass or compatible plastic/metal container resistant to oxidizers
â— Compatible With: Dry inorganic salts, inert solids
â— Incompatible With: Organic compounds, strong acids, reducing agents, flammable
materials
76
ğŸš¨ Safety Notes
â— First Aid:
â—‹ Skin: Wash thoroughly with soap and water; remove contaminated clothing.
â—‹ Eye: Rinse with water for at least 15 minutes; seek medical attention.
â—‹ Inhalation: Move to fresh air; seek medical attention if irritation occurs.
â—‹ Ingestion: Toxic; seek immediate medical attention.
â— Firefighting: Supports combustion; use large amounts of water to cool surrounding
combustibles. Do not use dry chemical extinguishers directly on bulk material.
â— Spill/Leak Cleanup: Avoid dust formation; sweep carefully with non-combustible tools.
Collect in a sealed container and keep away from heat and combustible materials.
ğŸ§‘â€ğŸ”¬ Lab Use Notes
â— PPE: Lab coat, gloves, goggles, dust mask/respirator if handling powder.
â— Handling: Avoid contamination with fuels, reducing agents, acids, and organic materials.
Handle only with clean, dry tools.
â— Decomposition Products: Oxygen (Oâ‚‚) and strontium oxide (SrO) when heated.
â— Disposal: Treat as hazardous oxidizer; follow local regulations. Do not release into the
environment.
âš ï¸ Note: Strontium peroxide is a strong oxidizer and can react violently with organic
compounds, acids, or reducing agents. Extreme caution is required during handling, storage,
and disposal.
