NFPA 704 System
The NFPA Diamond is split into four quadrants:
â— ğŸ”´ Red (Top): Flammability
â— ğŸ”µ Blue (Left): Health Hazard
â— ğŸŸ¡ Yellow (Right): Reactivity
â— âšª White (Bottom): Special Hazards
ğŸ”µ Health (Blue) â€“ Toxicity / Exposure Risk
â— 0 = No hazard
â— 1 = Slight irritation
â— 2 = Temporary injury, PPE required
â— 3 = Serious injury likely, fume hood required
â— 4 = Deadly with short exposure
ğŸ”´ Fire (Red) â€“ Flammability
â— 0 = Will not burn
â— 1 = Ignites only above 200 Â°F
â— 2 = Ignites above 100 Â°F
â— 3 = Flash point below 100 Â°F
â— 4 = Extremely flammable, gas at room temp
ğŸŸ¡ Reactivity (Yellow) â€“ Stability
81
â— 0 = Stable, even under fire
â— 1 = Unstable at high temp/pressure
â— 2 = Violent chemical change possible
â— 3 = May detonate with shock/heat
â— 4 = Readily explosive at room temp
âšª Special Hazards (White)
â— OX = Oxidizer
â— WÌ¶= Reacts violently with water
â— COR = Corrosive
â— RAD = Radioactive
82
